\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Content of Audit Records
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To ensure forensic viability and individual accountability,
 every generated audit record shall contain the following mandatory data elements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Timestamp
\series default
:
 The exact date and time the event occurred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Identity
\series default
:
 The unique identifier (e.g.,
 username,
 service account ID) of the individual or process causing the event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Event Type
\series default
:
 A clear categorization of the action attempted or executed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Outcome
\series default
:
 An indicator of success or failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Originating Source
\series default
:
 The logical or physical origin of the request (e.g.,
 source IP address,
 MAC address,
 terminal identifier).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Target Asset
\series default
:
 The name,
 identifier,
 or file path of the system,
 application,
 or data record impacted by the event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Clarification
\series default
:
 Audit records capturing personally identifiable information — including usernames,
 network addresses,
 and data manipulation records — inherit the privacy controls defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Privacy and Data Protection Policy).
 Standing up a new centralized log aggregation system or extending an existing system to process a new personal information category may qualify as a Privacy Impact Assessment trigger under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Log Centralization,
 Capacity,
 and Tamper Protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To satisfy separation of duties and protect audit integrity,
 the Information Operations Department shall configure audit logs to be protected from unauthorized modification,
 deletion,
 and spoofing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Storage Capacity
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall allocate audit record storage capacity sufficient to prevent logs from being overwritten or dropped prior to scheduled archival.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Centralized Repository
\series default
:
 The System and Network Administrators shall configure information systems to forward audit records continuously to a centralized,
 logically isolated log management repository.
 Batch forwarding intervals shall not exceed fifteen (15) minutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Append-Only Enforcement
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall enforce append-only or read-only privileges for all System and Network Administrators on the centralized repository.
 Personnel with administrative control over security baselines or system configurations shall not possess the capability to modify or delete audit logs that record their actions,
 in accordance with the Separation of Duties Matrix maintained under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Tamper Detection
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure the centralized log repository employs cryptographic mechanisms — including file hashing — and access control monitoring to detect unauthorized modifications to archived log files.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Log Repository Access Controls
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall control and monitor access to the centralized log repository to preserve audit record integrity and confidentiality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Access Authorization
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall approve all accounts granted read access to the centralized log repository.
 Base access control under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 applies;
 this section establishes additional audit-specific controls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Read-Only by Default
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall configure the default access level for authorized personnel as read-only.
 Write access to the repository shall be restricted to designated administrative service accounts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Administrator Separation
\series default
:
 Personnel whose routine duties include administering systems that generate audit records shall not serve as the sole reviewer of their own administrative logs,
 in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Meta-Logging
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure all access to the centralized log repository — including read,
 query,
 and export operations — is itself logged in the repository.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Export Controls
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall restrict log extraction to named administrators authorized for forensic support,
 compliance reporting,
 or legal hold response.
 Exported audit records shall inherit the classification of the source data and shall be handled in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Audit-of-the-Auditor Review
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall review the meta-log of repository access no less than quarterly to identify anomalous access patterns by authorized personnel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Audit Review,
 Analysis,
 Alerting,
 and Finding Routing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department shall proactively analyze audit records to detect anomalous activity,
 unauthorized access attempts,
 and potential security incidents,
 and shall route findings to appropriate downstream response and compliance processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Review Frequency
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure designated Tier L3 personnel conduct formal review of aggregated security audit logs no less than weekly,
 evidenced by a documented review record in the System of Engagement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Automated Alerting
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure automated tools are configured to generate real-time alerts for critical security events,
 including multiple failed authentication attempts,
 unauthorized access to CJI repositories,
 and detection of malicious code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Alert Routing
\series default
:
 System-generated security alerts shall be transmitted in real-time to the Assistant IT Director and designated Tier L3 System Administrators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Alert Review Service Levels
\series default
:
 Designated Tier L3 Administrators shall acknowledge and review alerts within the following time windows,
 measured from alert generation:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Critical
\series default
:
 Acknowledgment and triage initiation within fifteen (15) minutes,
 twenty-four (24) hours per day,
 seven (7) days per week.
 Full review shall complete within the High tier window.
 Applies to confirmed Indicator of Compromise (IoC) conditions,
 unauthorized access to CJI,
 and confirmed malicious code execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
High
\series default
:
 Full review within one (1) hour,
 twenty-four (24) hours per day,
 seven (7) days per week.
 Applies to multiple failed authentication events,
 privileged operation anomalies,
 and unauthorized configuration changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Medium and Routine
\series default
:
 By the end of the next business day.
 Applies to informational security events and single-threshold failed authentication events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Tier Assignment
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall establish alert tier assignments in the alerting configuration.
 Tier assignments shall be reviewable during scheduled audit.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Finding Routing
\series default
:
 Designated Tier L3 Administrators shall route audit findings to the appropriate downstream process:
\end_layout

